  "summary": "An interfaith, ecological Freedom Seder that links spring, ritual foods, Exodus, civil-rights history, and responsibility for the living earth. Its strongest sequences are vivid and participatory, while its 2009 political examples, expansive theological interpretations, songs, and embedded quotations must remain visibly sourced and historically framed.",
  "sourceAssessment": {
    "voice": "Prophetic, poetic, interfaith, ecological, and workshop-oriented, with an embodied theology of God as the interbreathing life of the world.",
    "bestUses": [
      "Environmental and interfaith theme paths",
      "Longer participatory Seders with room for communal reading and action",
      "Explanations of matzah, maror, charoset, Miriam's Cup, and the four cups",
      "Historical framing for the modern Freedom Seder movement"
    ],
    "beginnerRisks": [
      "The source's preferred names for God and its prophetic metaphors need plain-language introduction rather than silent substitution.",
      "Several ecological descriptions of the biblical plagues are interpretive midrash, not historical or scientific explanations.",
      "Many songs, poems, speeches, and translations are embedded third-party material with their own printed credits.",
      "Campaign suggestions, contact information, and policy examples date from 2009 and should not be presented as current guidance."
    ],
    "politicalContext": "The source openly advocates ecological, economic, anti-war, and civil-rights action. Use those passages only when the selected themes support them, label named campaigns and political examples as historical, and retain its peace-centered, non-exclusivist language. References to biblical Israel, ancient Jerusalem, Christianity, and Islam are historical or interfaith context rather than contemporary territorial claims.",
    "creditContext": "Credit Rabbi Arthur Waskow, The Shalom Center, and The Freedom Seder for the Earth on the final sources page. Preserve each embedded writer, translator, musician, or speaker credit and the source's printed permission line where required."
  },
